Modelling terms

  • response = outcome variable = dependent variable
  • fixed effect = predictor variable = independent variable
  • random effect = group-level effect = individual-specific effect

Preference

  • emmeans:: for pairwise comparisons of variable contrasts.

  • ggeffects:: for visualisation of interactions

  • modelbased:: for extracting interaction effect

  • ggplot2:: + modelbased:: for highly customized visualisation

Two predictor variables

  • Categorical x Categorical
  • Continuous x Categorical
  • Continuous x Continuous

Data Analytic Flow

1) Model statistics

model <- lm(Y ~ A * B, data = data)

summary(model)

car::Anova(model, type = “III”)

2) Report interaction statistics

emmeans(model, pairwise ~ A | B)

ggemmeans(model, terms = c(“A”, “B”))

estimate_contrasts(model, contrast = “A”, at = “B”)

estimate_slopes(model, trend = “A”, at = “B”)

3) Visualising interaction

emmeans(model, pairwise ~ A | B) %>% plot(comparisons = T)

ggemmeans(model, terms = c(“A”, “B”)) %>% plot()

estimate_slopes(model, trend = “A”, at = “B”) %>% plot()

Analysing Interactions

emmeans::emmeans(model, pairwise ~ varA | varB, type = “response”)

ggeffects::ggemmeans(model, terms = c(“varB”, “varA”))

modelbased::estimate_contrasts(model, contrast = “varA”, at = “varB”) or modelbased::estimate_slopes(model, trend = “varA”, at = “varB”)

Continuous x Categorical

Report interaction statistics: emmeans

emmeans::emmeans(mod2_cue, pairwise ~ cues | age, type = "response")$contrasts %>%
    data.frame() %>%
    select(-df, -null) %>%
    mutate_if(is.numeric, funs(round(., 3)))
  • perhaps ok, if the goal is to control for age rather than understanding age-related effect
  • especially when the relationship between continuous variable and response variable is linear and well-studied
  • but then, adding continuous variable as covariate (i.e., standalone predictor without interaction terms) could achieve the same goal, unless still suspect interactions of some sort

Continuous x Categorical

Report interaction statistics: ggeffects

ggeffects::ggemmeans(mod2_cue, terms = c("age [all]", "cues")) %>%
    data.frame() %>%
    mutate_if(is.numeric, funs(round(., 3))) %>%
    sample_n(nrow(.)/5) %>%
    arrange(x)

showed us the predicted proportion of group (i.e., cues) across x (i.e., age) as a continuous variable!

showed us statistics at cues and the associated age trend. great for summarising the relations.

Interaction statistics

Continuous x Continuous:

predicted/estimated means means contrasts coefficient visualisation informative?
emmeans() yes, but quirky no no no
ggemmeans() yes, continuous stays continuous no no show curves with third variable cross-sectional
estimate_slopes() no no yes show effect/coefficient/slope across full range of third variable

Continuous x Continuous

  • ggeffect show curves, i.e., how variable X predicts outcome Z, with a third variable, Y, cross-sectionally
  • ggeffect show relation between of variable X and outcome Z or variable Y and outcome Z, but not simultaneously
  • requires 2 graphs to visualise interactions between X and Y against Z

Continuous x Continuous

alternative:

  • estimate_means() +

  • geom_contour_filled() or

  • geom_raster() or

  • geom_tile()
